entry.title: [iOS] Fixing iOS17 EG Bookmarks test failures
entry.content:
In iOS 17, when the Bookmarks UI is being shutdown, both the

`BookmarksHomeViewController` and the `UISearchController` embedded

inside the `BookmarksHomeViewController` dismissal functionality are

being invoked. This double invocation is causing a crash because a

property that has been set to null by the `BookmarksHomeViewController`

dismissal function is being used in the `UISearchController` dismissal

function. To get around this, `UISearchController` is being explicitly

dismissed during the shutdown process.

entry.title: [dPWA] Parameterize ML promotion tests on the basis of dialogs
entry.content:
This CL parameterizes all the ML promotion browser tests to take into

account all sorts of dialogs that can be interacted with the web app

system. To do so:

that measures installation not triggered by ML also take into account

the Create Shortcut dialog.

entry.title: [RemoveLegacy] Remove NeedsPositionedMovementLayout flag.
entry.content:
This flag was used when an inset/margin changed on non-static

positioned elements.



In NG we didn't skip the LayoutResult cache if it was marked as dirty

with this flag, and legacy performed a special type of "movement"

layout when dirty.



We don't need this flag anymore, instead we can directly invalidate

the containing block (needing "simplified" layout if the element is

OOF positioned, or "normal" layout if not).



This patch will likely result in some elements not requiring full

layout anymore. E.g. DependenceOnContentHeightHasChanged triggered a

full layout on a rel-pos element when not required.



For rel-pos we could always just require "simplified" layout if we

undid the rel-pos offset, then recalculated it correctly. There is

some complexity with %-insets under this scheme however.

entry.title: Fix two custom elements tests to avoid depending on undefined ordering.
entry.content:
Each test file has a single test that is currently failing identically

in both Chromium and Gecko, while passing in WebKit.



The tests that fail invoke:

document.open(URL, "_self", "");

in a custom element constructor, and then rely on a script element

*following* the custom element to be executed.



This change fixes the test to avoid depending on that following script,

but instead run the necessary code in the custom element constructor.

(Only the test that does the document.open(URL, "_self", "") call needs

this change, but the change affects all the tests in these files.)



I believe the current test is depending on undefined behavior because

(although I fully admit I'm skimming relatively long lists of complex

steps in the HTML specification quite quickly) the document.open call is

specified at

https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/C#dom-document-open-window which

invokes https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/C#window-open-steps where

either step 12.6 or 13.1.3 are the same and invoke

https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/C#navigate . Step 19 of that

algorithm is run "in parallel"), and step 19.3 invokes

https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/C#abort-a-document which in turn

invokes https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/C#abort-a-parser which I

believe will stop later scripts from executing. The definition of "in

parallel" is explicitly undefined at

https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/C#in-parallel so it's not clear

when the parser is aborted relative to other things. I think this means

that either the Gecko/Chromium behavior of aborting the parser before

executing the following script, or the WebKit behavior of aborting at

some later time, are both permitted.

entry.content:
Previously, running the ax_dump_tree utility with Firefox would crash

because we only check for SUCCEEDED when querying the ISimpleDomNode API. Firefox was returning S_FALSE and the code went on doing logic on a

APIs, so I was wondering if I can just delete that code altogether. But it seems to still be in use for MathML, so I guess we can't do that.

entry.title: Make AutofillSuggestionTriggerSource available to selected suggestions.
entry.content:
When suggestions are generated, the AutofillSuggestionTriggerSource

describes what caused the suggestions to appear (e.g. "clicked into a

field", "edited a text field", etc). This information generally

originates from the renderer, where some Blink event triggered the

suggestion. It makes its way to the browser process and to the external

delegate, which triggers the popup.



When a suggestion is accepted/selected, the popup notifies the external

delegate through Did(Accept|Select)Suggestion(). At this point, the

AutofillSuggestionTriggerSource is currently not available.

For manual fallbacks, this information is necessary, since suggestions

triggered through manual fallbacks behave differently (they fill

ac=unrecognized fields).



This CL makes the AutofillSuggestionTriggerSource available to

Did(Accept|Select)Suggestion() by:

- Replacing AutofillClient::PopupOpenArgs::autoselect_first_suggestion

by the trigger source, and passing on the trigger source to the

popup controller's Show() function.

From the trigger source, the autoselect_first_suggestion property can

be derived (the first suggestion is auto-selected in the

kTextFieldDidReceiveKeyDown case).

- Storing the trigger source in the popup controller.

- Adding a trigger source parameter to Did(Accept|Select)Suggestion().

- When a suggestion is accepted/selected, pass on the trigger source

stored in the controller to the external delegate.



For the most part, this is straightforward. However, in some cases, no

trigger source is available (specifically, for Android WebView, iOS and

password manager popups). For them, separate new trigger sources are

introduced to identify them. See autofill_types.mojom for details.

Since neither of the cases supports autoselect_first_suggestion (always

set to false), this ensures that the behavior is kept as-is.

The follow-up crrev.com/c/4603848 further cleans this up.



In Autofill tests, all occurrences of autoselect_first_suggestion false

are replaced with trigger source kFormControlElementClicked (the most

common trigger source). For the password manager, the newly introduced

kPasswordManager source is used.

apply. The values are simply added to a switch in the NOTREACHED() case.

entry.title: Add browser tests for hash-prefix real-time lookups
entry.content:
Similarly to the URL real-time lookup browser tests, this does not mock

network requests. It instead mocks the results by modifying the local

HPRT cache. The purpose of this is to avoid adding redundant tests,

since HashRealTimeService already has sufficient unit test coverage.



Specific things covered:

- A navigation triggers an interstitial if the HashRealTimeService says

the URL is unsafe and the feature is enabled. (And conversely, it

doesn't if the URL is safe or if the feature is disabled.)

- The HPRT-specific interstitial.*.decision metric is triggered

appropriately (from a navigation resulting in a warning shown).

- The HPRT-specific SafeBrowsing.BrowserThrottle.TotalDelay2 metric is

triggered appropriately from a navigation.

- The SafeBrowsing.HPRT.Ineligible.* logs are triggered on navigation.

- The HPRT-specific types of hit reports and CSBRRs are logged.

entry.title: Add a mechanism for invalidating SVG viewport dependencies
entry.content:
Add a flag to LayoutObject that tracks if the LayoutObject or any of its

descendants depend on the viewport dimension. Update this flag when

style is updated. For containers, the flag is cleared lazily on layout.



Use this mechanism to fix an issue where an SVG element which has

'transform-box: view-box' and a transform that depends on the reference

box would not get properly updated if the viewport changed.



It is hoped that this mechanism can be extended to support the general

case of viewport dependencies, and thus replace the existing mechanism

for that in SVGElement (c.f crbug.com/709437).

entry.title: Fix Chromeguard crash
entry.content:
A CHECK is hit when the CookieControlsObserver fires an update event

in close proximity to the close of the CookieControlsBubbleView.



In particular, this can occur when the active tab changes to a tab

which has cookie controls disabled (such as a chrome:// URL). When

this happens, it breaks the expectation that the UI is not shown over such pages, and the CHECK enforcing that expectation is hit.



The UI is not _really_ shown, as it is in the process of closing

(i.e. WindowClosing() has already been called), but an attempt to

update the title is made based on the new CookieControlsObserver

information is made anyway.



This CL ensures that the bubble stops observing the CookieControls

when CloseBubble is called, preventing future updates be handled.



The test introduced in this CL reliably fails without the associated

fix.

entry.content:
This CL newly adds lcp_critical_path_predictor table to store

lcp_element_locator histogram, and plumbs the write path of the field

restriction. LearnLcpp() uses a virtual sliding window. The sliding

window size can be changed with lcpp_histogram_sliding_window_size (the

default size is 1000). The detailed explanation of the LearnLcpp() is

written in the following document.

entry.title: Make calc(NaN) behave as calc(0) when it's top level calculation
entry.content:
https://www.w3.org/TR/css-values-4/#top-level-calculation



calc-interpolation.html test changes due to the CSS Values 4 spec:



Dividing zero by zero, dividing Â±âˆž by Â±âˆž, multiplying 0 by Â±âˆž,

adding +âˆž to âˆ’âˆž (or the equivalent subtractions) produces NaN.



Interpolation of math functions, with each other or with numeric values

and other numeric-valued functions, is defined as

Vresult = calc((1 - p) * Va + p * Vb).



This means that the interpolation at p=0 is: calc((1 - 0) * 0px + 0 * (infinity * 1px), which simplifies to calc(0px + NaN), which should clamp to 0px.



Fixed: 1334599
